5|$|An {{equivalent}} active camouflage strategy, {{known to}} zoologists as counter-illumination, {{is used by}} many marine organisms, notably cephalopods such as the midwater squid, Abralia veranyi. The underside is covered with small photophores, organs that produce light. The squid varies {{the intensity of the}} light according to the brightness of the <b>sea</b> <b>surface</b> far above, providing effective camouflage by painting out the animal's silhouette with light.|$|E
